@David Connell There were times as I read particular passages in Moby Dick for the first time that I felt like the air around me was buzzing in the way people describe the last few moments before being hit by lightning.

I had a friend whose bedroom was a shrine to Melville; a harpoon on her wall, multiple editions of Moby Dick, a real whale-oil candle that she found while on a pilgramage to Nantucket which she did me the honor of lighting (the smell made me think of old buildings and invoked strong deja-vu).

Hemmingway, though... my only encounter with Hemmingway was in the seventh grade at age 11, when I picked "The Old Man and the Sea" for a book report and spent days trying to figure out what was meant by it. It was miserable enough that I haven't read anything further by him since. I should probably do something about that...

